==Old English==
===Etymology===
West Germanic *''[[kokar-]]'', whence also Old Frisian ''[[koker]]'', Old Saxon ''kokar'' (Dutch ''[[koker]]''), Old High German ''[[kohhar|kohhār]]'' (German ''[[Köcher]]''). The origin of the West Germanic word is unknown, but note that a similar word can be found in the Turkic languages meaning "skin bottle", "hose", including Altay [[кӧкӧр]], Kazakh [[көккөр]]
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'koker/

===Noun===
'''cocer''' ''m''

# a [[quiver]] for arrows

